### Describe the bug

When we configure 2 authentication schemes and specify the non-default authentication scheme using the `[Authorize]` attribute, the default scheme is still challenged, while this shouldn't be the case.


```csharp
services.AddAuthentication(defaultScheme: "One"))
    .AddJwtBearer(authenticationScheme: "One", o => { })
    .AddJwtBearer(authenticationScheme: "Two", o => { });
```

```csharp
[ApiController]
[Route("api/test"]
public class TestController : ControllerBase
{
    [HttpGet]
    [Authorize(AuthenticationSchemes = "Two")]
    public IActionResult Get()
    {
       return Ok();
    }
}
```

The problem is, when we do the api-call to `api/test` with a token that is valid for the second JwtBearer scheme (scheme "Two"), we get into the handler, but also get back a `WWW-Authenticate` header with the error `invalid_token`, generated by the first JwtBearer scheme (the default scheme, "One"). In the case of returning `Ok()` our HTTP status code is still 200, but when we return a `FileContentResult` for example, we get back the file content + a 401 HTTP status code + the `WWW-Authenticate` header with the `invalid_token`.

I guess this issue is closely related to https://github.com/dotnet/aspnetcore/issues/17485 but there was no real solution to the original issue and I cannot re-open it.

### Expected Behavior

The expected behavior is, when we specify a scheme in the `AuthorizeAttribute`, ASP.NET Core should no longer trigger the default scheme.

### Steps To Reproduce

```csharp
services.AddAuthentication(defaultScheme: "One"))
    .AddJwtBearer(authenticationScheme: "One", o => { })
    .AddJwtBearer(authenticationScheme: "Two", o => { });

services.AddAuthorization();
services.AddControllers();

...

app.UseRouting();
app.UseAuthorization();
app.UseAuthentication();
app.UseEndpoints(configure => configure.MapControllers());
```

```csharp
[ApiController]
[Route("api/test"]
public class TestController : ControllerBase
{
    [HttpGet]
    [Authorize(AuthenticationSchemes = "Two")]
    public IActionResult Get()
    {
       return Ok();
    }
}
```

### Exceptions (if any)

_No response_

### .NET Version

Tested with 5.0 and 6.0

### Anything else?

Tested with ASP.NET Core 5 and 6.

